# Preface {.unnumbered}

This site is designed to provide a comprehensive and structured guide for beginners seeking to set up a Linux-based working environment—specifically using distributions such as Fedora and Ubuntu—for academic and laboratory use. It aims to support users with limited prior experience by offering clear, step-by-step instructions and practical recommendations to facilitate a smooth and efficient setup process.

The primary objective of this site is to help users establish a functional and productive computing environment tailored to research and data analysis tasks commonly encountered in laboratory settings.

The contents of this site are organized as follows:

## 1. Linux Installation

Detailed guidance on installing popular Linux distributions (e.g., Fedora and Ubuntu), including system requirements, partitioning, and initial configuration.

## 2. Emacs Setup

Instructions for installing and configuring Emacs as a powerful and customizable text editor, with particular emphasis on features useful for programming, LaTeX editing, and research workflows.

## 3. Stata Installation

Step-by-step procedures for installing and setting up Stata on a Linux system, along with basic configuration to ensure compatibility and efficient usage for data analysis.

Together, these sections provide a foundational framework for building a reliable and research-oriented Linux environment.
